MARK YOUR CALENDARS!! Pre-order for my SS23 collection opens May 19th at 5pm EST! Shop your favorite looks from my NYFW runway. 

I have a bunch of styles coming and I am working with a variety of manufacturers (including sewing some myself!) I am trying my best to make this drop as affordable and size inclusive as possible. my favorite (dare i say ✨iconic✨) outfit of the collection - this one is very personal for me and was honestly the jumping off point for the entire concept. The You Have Time graphic came from sticky notes I put up on the big yellow decal above my bed one night when I was feeling anxious and out of control. I (and many of us I think) sometimes tend to overthink things have the urge to act impulsively and try to fix things that aren’t broken before taking the time to understand the root of why we’re anxious. Sometimes all it takes is a little time and perspective to see that everything was okay all along. Seeing this reminder on my wall every day was my way to take a step back when I felt anxious, give it time, and sometimes sit with the discomfort that I feel in order to prove to myself that everything is okay. I have since moved and no longer have the decal on my wall, but i love wearing this tee as my new form of reminder and I hope it helps you in a similar way <3

TODAY IS THE LAST DAY to pre order my NYFW collection EMERGENCE!! 

This collection is about my transition into adulthood - I always felt like I was meant to be in my 20s, and it’s sometimes easy to forget that while transitions are exciting, they come with a lot of discomfort while you grow. It is vulnerable and intense, and sometimes you just need that reminder to slow down and that everything will work out in time. 

I have LOVED working on this collection and I have learned so much from my first production run. I started this collection on New Year’s Eve of 2022 so it’s been in my world for a while, it has evolved so much and I am excited to close this chapter and move on to the next. 

Thank you so much for all the love on this one, can’t wait to see you wear it!! Click the link in my bio TODAY to shop these styles before they’re gone 💕

When I first started my fashion education, i would always get the same feedback over and over - sloooow down. My process has always been chaotic and i love it that way - i almost never follow an order of operations and prefer to break the rules. 

BUT!! i have found so much enjoyment lately in attention to detail - tiny, tedious, repetitive techniques, projects that are mindless and meditative - i started with upcycling a pair of boots by bedazzling them in tens of thousands of rhinestones, and lately i’ve been learning tambour embroidery!!! I started with the basics but am starting to get the hang of it and am branching out into embroidering some 3D flower appliqués. 

There’s no such thing as a small project for me so i am jumping right into designing a full couture collection…it’s a more sophisticated spin off of my monsters collection from 2018, exploring the topic of mental health, and learning to accept and love our inner monsters as a beautiful part of ourselves. Personally I have named mine Cora - giving her a name makes it easier for me to have compassion for her - and also tell her to f*** off sometimes, whether she listens or not 😂 - and also allows me to separate her from myself and give myself a break when things get a little intense.

welcome to my very chaotic process if you’re new, there is no consistency here! can’t wait to keep developing and keep learning. 

xoxo
emma

introducing CORA - the next chapter for @emmarubinsonofficial 🪻🌸🌻 

Inspired by my many years of struggling with PMDD, this collection is an ode to my inner monster, Cora. She drives me nuts sometimes but naming her has helped me separate her from myself, and have compassion for her. The past year or two especially has been a huge turning point in learning how to take care of her, and we’re getting *a little* closer to being friends. 

We all have an inner monster in some way, maybe they judge us, bully us, or make it hard to be our true and unapologetic selves. With this collection I hope to inspire you to get to know yours - because at the end of the day, we all have them and they are what make us complex, beautiful, and able to relate to each other. Kill ‘em with kindness just like you would a real live middle school bully and eventually they’ll come around 💕 (easier said than done i know…but i’m an optimist what can i say)

I’ve already been exploring and sharing a bunch of new techniques that I will be using in this collection, and i hope it will be a collage of chaos and beauty. Not sure when it will launch yet since I’m taking my time but I’m so excited to share the process with you!!

xoxo
emma

What are your thoughts on AI art??

I’ve been using Midjourney as a creative development tool lately and have found it to be such a cool resource to generate ideas. While it never gives me exactly what I think I am describing, it suggests silhouettes, textiles, and color palettes I wouldn’t have thought of on my own. 

I struggle to call these images “my work” because I didn’t exactly put any “work” into them the way I do my real garments, especially since the real live humans that are involved in my work are the most important part. There are many aspects of AI that are absolutely terrifying and problematic, but it does seem to be the way of the future in some kind of way. 

From an artist perspective at least, I know that I am the only one able to generate these silhouettes with my wording and prompts and it’s very cool to see that my art style still really comes through. I think it’s an amazing tool for artists to expand their creativity and get inspired. So much more interesting and specific than building a pinterest board I think, and it allows me to implement my research in a really cool visual way!

Images here created with Midjourney for concept development of my couture collection CORA 🌸💕

7 (!!!) years ago today was the day I discovered my passion for immersive fashion and art. 

After waiting in line for almost 9 hours in the NYC august heat with @maggie.milller @georgiamanning and @izabelaraczkowski (honorable mention to my dad who tapped out after 3), we entered @refinery29 ‘s NYFW exhibit, @29rooms 

Each room was a curated environment with a different theme - the exhibit centered on the theme “Powered by People” and gave everyone who came through a chance to participate in the art by recording a voicemail, voting their values, and expressing their true colors. 

I was so inspired by the interactive nature of this experience, and fell in love with watching the exhibit come together as a combination of the perspectives of the public. 

Walking into each room felt like entering a new little world of creation and I dreamed of someday giving my own audience the same space. About 10 months later, I created my own version to share before graduating high school - you can find it on my website under Meraki. 

I’m still dreaming of creating another interactive world, and have been brainstorming a lot lately about what that will look like at at this point in my life. Things are slowly coming together. Everything I share on here is with that end goal in mind and I’m excited to have you here with me as it unfolds 💕

xoxo
emma

“Fashion designer, textile artist, color specialist & content creator based in NYC, Emma Rubinson’s work explores the human experience. Inspired by dreams, alternate realities, and psychological phenomena, she aims to empower people to embrace and express the true colors of their inner souls. She is constantly inspired by interactions with deep thinkers and big dreamers.”

I’ve been sharing the behind the scenes of my own work, patternmaking and sewing tutorials, fashion designer resources, and more on Instagram and TikTok for the past 3 and a half years, and I’ve decided it’s time to take it IRL!

If you haven’t already heard, I’m partnering with @brooklynsewingacademy and hosting a pop up patternmaking workshop in NYC 🥳 Stay tuned later this week for details regarding dates, pricing, and what to expect in each of the 3 sessions. 

You can read the rest of my artist’s statement and see my portfolio of work on my website.
